Tune into this week's episode as @dogfishhead founders Sam and Mariah uncover the importance of land and water conservation at both Bristol Marsh Preserve and Cove Mountain Preserve. They also take a trip to Staten Island, NY to see how TNC is working to benefit communities impacted by Hurricane Sandy. 

As always, more on this epic roadtrip via our link in bio!

@dogfishhead co-founders Sam and Mariah Calagione embarked on an epic & eco-friendly road trip from Florida to Maine, learning all about TNC's conservation efforts along the way. 

In this episode, Sam and Mariah take a deep dive into the history behind Bear Island/Potomac Gorge in Maryland and the significance of our oyster aquaculture and restoration work amidst the pandemic. They also get a close-up look at how TNC is bringing nature's benefits to urban residents in Wilmington, Delaware. 

More on this road trip adventure and our work with @dogfishhead via our link in bio!

node.text:
Nature's health has always been a priority to @dogfishhead's founder and brewer, Sam Calagione. “Mother Nature, Let’s Do This!” (developed in tandem with TNC) follows Sam and his wife and co-founder Mariah as they embark on an epic and eco-friendly East Coast road trip from Florida to Maine. There, they hear more about TNC’s efforts to conserve our lands and waters, speak to local, environmental experts and explore Mother Nature’s splendors. 

In this episode, Sam and Mariah get their feet wet (literally!) with visits to our Blowing Rocks Preserve in @natureflorida, Goldbug Island Living Shoreline in South Carolina and the Black River Preserve in North Carolina. 

More on this road trip adventure and our work with @dogfishhead via our link in bio!

There’s a remarkable, intricate world of biodiversity just below the surface of the temporary ponds that form in our forests. Vernal pools fill up in spring as the winter snows melt. For a few months, they host breeding events for amphibians and macroinvertebrates.

A look inside the worlds of alien vernal pools from the latest issue of Nature Conservancy Magazine via our link in bio! 

Video by @stevendavidjohnsonphoto and @awilesmedia

node.text:
People are influenced by what–and WHO they see. It's #BlackinNationalParks week–an opportunity to highlight those who are pushing for a racially diverse, equitable, and inclusive representation of the outdoors. 

"I've always felt that the national parks are places for everyone... that means me, that means you. As an African-American Park Ranger, I can show young people that they have greater choices than they ever imagined." Thank you, Shelton, for sharing your story!

node.text: On July 15, 2010, the recovery of the Gulf of Mexico truly began. The Deepwater Horizon oil spill was officially capped, giving Gulf communities the opportunity to finally look forward, and begin the process of considering what recovery could truly mean. Here is a look at some of what The Nature Conservancy and our partners have been doing over the past decade... and what we see for the future.

@dogfishhead co-founders Sam and Mariah Calagione embarked on an epic & eco-friendly road trip from Florida to Maine, learning all about TNC's conservation efforts along the way. 

In this episode, Sam and Mariah take a deep dive into the history behind Bear Island/Potomac Gorge in Maryland and the significance of our oyster aquaculture and restoration work amidst the pandemic. They also get a close-up look at how TNC is bringing nature's benefits to urban residents in Wilmington, Delaware. 

More on this road trip adventure and our work with @dogfishhead via our link in bio!

Why is nature so therapeutic? For some, it's a welcome respite in a busy world. For others, it's where we find ourselves when we're lost. 

Whether it's in the stillness of a forest, the quiet of a morning or the simplicity of a breeze, nature has healing power.  And sometimes this is manifested best... by  speaking directly to nature. 

@grangersmith knows this to be true as he recently found peace in nature after losing his son, River. Check out our stories for the beautiful tribute. 💚

#natureheals #peopleandnature #peace #naturenurtures

Nature's health has always been a priority to @dogfishhead's founder and brewer, Sam Calagione. “Mother Nature, Let’s Do This!” (developed in tandem with TNC) follows Sam and his wife and co-founder Mariah as they embark on an epic and eco-friendly East Coast road trip from Florida to Maine. There, they hear more about TNC’s efforts to conserve our lands and waters, speak to local, environmental experts and explore Mother Nature’s splendors. 

In this episode, Sam and Mariah get their feet wet (literally!) with visits to our Blowing Rocks Preserve in @natureflorida, Goldbug Island Living Shoreline in South Carolina and the Black River Preserve in North Carolina. 

More on this road trip adventure and our work with @dogfishhead via our link in bio!

node.text:
As #IndependenceDay approaches in the United States, we're thinking about how the future of people and of the natural world depends on bold, collective action. By working together to conserve, restore, and protect that natural world we can maintain the productivity of our working lands and waters, clean the air we breathe and the water we drink, and ensure that we and our children and grandchildren can thrive and enjoy the wonders of the natural world that is the foundation of all life. 

To do our part to meet this challenge, the US has pledged to conserve and restore 30 percent of its lands and waters by 2030 through an initiative known as: America the Beautiful. This will take a collaborative effort literally from the ground up that includes us all -  farmers, foresters, fishers and ranchers, people living and working in rural and urban areas, and Indigenous peoples.

The health and vitality of our land and water is under greater stress than at any other time in human history. If we want to sustain all of this, we must act. Learn about the places you love and find out how you can help preserve and protect them by signing up via our link in bio. 

#july4th #independenceday #preserveandprotect #landsandwaters 📸: Airon Mothershed
